Asymptomatic patients with NCP are easy to be ignored because of the lack of symptoms or almost no symptoms. These patients are also considered to be one of the difficulties in epidemic prevention and control.

February 26th, a team of researchers from the First Affiliated Hospital of the University of Science and Technology of China (Anhui Provincial Hospital) , the Anhui Medical University affiliated Anqing Hospital and the Anhui Provincial Center for Disease Control and Prevention submitted a new study (without peer review) on Chinaxiv, a pre-publication platform for Chinese Academy of Sciences Papers, the discovery and clinical treatment details of a patient with asymptomatic infection of a novel coronavirus are reported.

The study's corresponding authors were Weng Jianping, a professor in the University of Science and Technology of China's Department of life sciences and medicine, and Liu Jian, associate dean of the Anhui Medical University affiliated Anqing Hospital. According to the team, the study should be the first to report asymptomatic infection with the new coronavirus, the paper said.

The subject, a 50-year-old woman, tested positive for the new coronavirus by nucleic acid testing 20 days after the paper was submitted, but the nucleic acid test of the infected person had not turned negative by the time the paper was submitted. Based on clinical results, the team also concluded that the current treatment may not be effective for the infected person, but caused minor liver damage.

As a result, they suggest, patients who are asymptomatic or have mild symptoms may be at less risk from isolation and close observation.

In a news 1 + 1 broadcast on the evening of February 19, Wang Chen, a respiratory and critical care specialist and vice president of the Chinese Academy of Engineering, also responded to questions from asymptomatic infected people, he said, "The judgment of asymptomatic infection is mainly based on nucleic acid testing, and there will be antigen testing and antibody testing, which are effective means to identify asymptomatic infection. "

He also mentioned that the new coronavirus may also undergo certain changes in response to the biological characteristics it reflects, "As we deepen our understanding, we will develop some medical prevention, diagnosis and treatment methods, and make corresponding arrangements and prevention. "

Close monitoring is one option for finding asymptomatic patients, but it is costly

In February 2020, the team identified four family clusters of new coronavirus cases at the Anhui Medical University. One of the family members (YQ, patient a) was asymptomatic. At present, to ensure the quality of testing, Anhui Province implemented a two-step confirmation strategy, city-level CDC and provincial CDC confirmed respectively, the patient was finally diagnosed as new pneumonia.

Yq Is a 50-year-old woman who lives in Anqing with her husband, patient B. The couple, who have not been to Wuhan or nearby cities, also denied any contact with wild animals. The husband had close contact with his sister (patient c) and brother-in-law (patient d) between January 23 and January 25. Patient C and Patient D also had no travel history in Wuhan, but patient D had worked with patient e on January 21. Before meeting patient D, patient e returned to Anqing from Wuhan, where he was later diagnosed with new crown pneumonia.

Patient d developed a fever on January 26, and patient c developed a fever on January 30. They were first admitted to the second people's Hospital in Anqing and swabs were taken. On 5 February, the two patients were confirmed to be positive for the new coronavirus. After their diagnosis, they were immediately transferred to the Anhui Medical University.

As close contacts, both Yq and patient B received throat swabs and CT scans on the same day, although they did not have any symptoms of fever, cough or breathing. On February 6, Yq and patient B were confirmed as new coronavirus positive. CT SCAN of patient B showed ground-glass opacity (GGO) in the lower segment of right lung, which suggested viral infection. On February 6, Yq and patient B were admitted to Anhui Medical University Anqing Hospital for treatment and observation.

YQ has no history of hypertension, diabetes, chronic liver disease, chronic kidney disease, etc. . Vital signs were normal on admission, body temperature 36.6 °C, Pulse 88 times per minute, respiratory rate 20 times per minute, blood pressure 13690mmhg, Oxygenation 99% .

Since January 23, during hospitalization, YQ has not reported fever, fatigue, pain or any gastrointestinal and respiratory symptoms, including cough, sore throat, diarrhea or vomiting. The nurses and the doctors didn't notice any of these symptoms.

Without detailed epidemiological questioning and close monitoring, it is difficult to detect Yq, and even her husband, who has a positive throat swab and abnormal lungs on a CT scan, the team said during a discussion session, no other symptoms, either.

The couple was unaware of the infection before they were discovered and passed it on to others. Close monitoring of asymptomatic individuals will therefore be an option to prevent the spread of the disease in this way, but at a high cost.

A better solution, of course, might be to develop protective vaccines.

Between Feb. 6 and Feb. 16, after hospitalization, Yq received treatment with traditional Chinese Medicine (TCM) , atomized Interferon 2, and Lopinavir Ritonavir. She then discontinued TCM and Ritonavir and switched to intravenous riba Welling.

On February 16, her lab results were almost normal. On February 20, liver enzymes were slightly elevated, but she felt no change, and no signs or symptoms were observed. The liver protective agent glycyrrhizic acid was added to the treatment. Chest CT scans were also performed on 11 February and 20 February and were normal.

Notably, on February 19, YQ's second throat swab and its anal swab were tested, both of which were positive for the new coronavirus. As of the submission of the paper, YQ was still hospitalized, the authors note.

The team determined that based on current clinical analysis, YQ might be a healthy asymptomatic carrier of the virus.

In addition, although YQ was treated with TCM, Lopinavir, Ritonavir and Ribavirin during her two week hospitalization, her continued positive viral nucleic acid indicates that these treatments may not be effective.

This was also demonstrated in a randomized clinical trial conducted by another team. Earlier, on Feb. 21, Lu Hongzhou, a member of the Expert Group of the National Health Commission and Party secretary of the Shanghai Municipal Public Health Clinical Center, published a new study in the Chinese Journal of Infectious Diseases, they also reviewed clinical data from 134 patients with newly diagnosed pneumonia and found no improvement in symptoms or reduction in the time it takes for respiratory specimens to turn negative with Ritonavir, it is concluded that its effectiveness is still to be confirmed by further clinical studies. The same is true for another drug, Abidor.

In addition, in Yq, the elevated liver enzymes observed after treatment may be due to Lopinavir Ritonavir, a common side effect of which is liver injury.
